  "original_title": "\u0d86\u0dbb\u0dca\u0dae\u0dd2\u0d9a \u0db8\u0db0\u0dca\u200d\u0dba\u0dc3\u0dca\u0dae\u0dcf\u0db1 \u0db4\u0dcf\u0dbd\u0dd4\u0dc0\u0da7 \u0dba\u0dba\u0dd2",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Economic centers will be deserted",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "Economic centers including Peliyagoda Manning Market, Dambulla, Narahenpita Megoda and Bokundara were deserted today (7) due to the absence of consumers.",
        "Mr. Nimal Attanayake, Treasurer of All Lanka Integrated Economic Center and Manning Trade Association said that due to the drop in both the receipt of goods and the sale of goods, trading has become very difficult.",
        "He also mentioned that with the fuel crisis, the maintenance of economic centers has become very problematic.",
        "Due to this, many shops in some economic centers have been closed, our reporters say.",
        "It is also reported that the prices of vegetables and fruits have decreased compared to usual.",
        "According to this, in Peliyagoda Manning Market, a kilo of carrots is 250 rupees, a kilo of beans is 300 rupees, a kilo of cabbage is 200 rupees, a kilo of eggplant is 300 rupees, a kilo of leeks is 150 rupees, a kilo of pumpkin is 220 rupees, a kilo of green chillies is 500 rupees, a kilo of lime is 200 rupees and a kilo of tomatoes is \u20b9 150, customers say that it was sold.",
        "In addition to this, at Narahenpita Economic Center, carrots cost Rs 320 per kg, beans Rs 360 per kg, cabbage Rs 280 per kg, eggplant Rs 400 per kg, pumpkin Rs 200 per kg, green chillies Rs 800 per kg, lime Rs 700 per kg, tomatoes Rs 360 per kg, country Customers say that 240 kilos of potatoes, 420 kilos of Ceylon potatoes and 200 kilos of B onions were sold.",
        "Meanwhile, in the Peliyagoda fish market, talapat is sold at 1550 rupees, balaya 1000 rupees, salaya 800 rupees, hurulla 1000 rupees, linna 950 rupees etc."
      ],
